ce:section.ce:para:
Firstly, we separately evaluated the biocompatibility of CDs and CDsomes through in vitro cytotoxicity assays toward HeLa cells (human cervical adenocarcinoma cell line). The HeLa cells incubated with CDsomesnuc, CDscyto, and CDsomesmem all displayed negligible cytotoxicity up to 300 μg mL−1, revealing their high biocompatibility for cell imaging applications (Fig. S4). The fluorescence microscopy images of NIH-3T3 (mouse embryonic fibroblast cell line), HeLa, and MCF-7 (human breast adenocarcinoma cell line) cells after incubating with 200 μg mL−1 of either CDsomes or CDs clearly show the localization of CDsomesnuc, CDscyto, and CDsomesmem in the nucleolus, cytoplasm, and cell membrane, respectively (Fig. 2
                        ). Blue, green, and red fluorescence images of the cells were captured by using UV light (360–370 nm), blue light (460–490 nm), and green light (525–545 nm), respectively. Nucleolus-targeting CDsomesnuc indicated different sizes and quantities of nucleoli in different cell lines (Fig. 2A). In general, transformed cells have more and larger nucleoli than their normal counterparts in order to cope with high protein demands, which can be used as a distinctive cytological feature of cancer malignancies (Montanaro et al., 2008; Stępiński, 2018). The hydrophilic CDscyto are accumulated in the cytoplasm (Fig. 2B), whereas CDsomesmem are selectively located at membrane structures such as plasma membrane, nuclear membrane, and endoplasmic reticulum (ER) of the cell lines due to their lipophilicity (Fig. 2C). It is noteworthy that nuclear and plasma membranes are composed of double and single lipid bilayers, respectively (Yang et al., 2017; Ingólfsson et al., 2014). Therefore, a thicker staining pattern is observed on the nuclear membrane than that of on plasma membrane. In addition, the nuclear membrane forms an interconnected network with ER, an organelle featuring folded membranous structures around the nucleus, where an obvious staining pattern was observed after CDsomesmem labeling. We also demonstrated confocal laser scanning microscopy (CLSM) images of HeLa cells labeled with CDsomesnuc, CDscyto, and CDsomesmem (Fig. S5), which further demonstrated specific labeling of CDsomes/CDs on nucleolus, cytoplasm, and membrane, respectively. The 3D imaging reconstructed by a confocal microscope (
                           Supplementary Video 1
                        ) provided clear and discernible CDsomesnuc‒labeled nucleoli, again suggesting the organelle-targetability of these novel nanoprobes.

Rapid and suborganelle-selective labeling of CDscyto in living and dead cells were achieved through energy-independent diffusion. The effect of PFA fixation on CDscyto labeling is negligible, implying that free diffusion across the plasma membrane is mainly responsible for cytoplasmic localization. Also, short and few phospholipids-like hydrocarbon chains of pyrolyzed triglyceride residues onto the surface of CDscyto mimic the physicochemical environment of membrane, which provides a stronger interaction with the plasma membrane and facilitates cytoplasmic accumulation. It is widely known that phospholipid–conjugated CDs or amphiphilic CDs could be used for studying vesicle morphology and bilayer dynamics due to their facile incorporation into lipid bilayers (Nandi et al., 2014, 2016). Therefore, membrane fusion might be a possible explanation for the interaction of CDsomes with the plasma membrane of live and fixed/permeabilized cells. In addition, we believe that CDsomesnuc initiates membrane fusion with plasma membrane, while a portion of the CDsomesnuc with an intact vesicle structure aids in cellular internalization, and then the CDsomesnuc undergoes fusion with nuclear membrane to release and translocate the hydrophilic CDs to the nucleoli. The entry of CDsomesnuc into Hela cells was recorded (
                           Supplementary Video 2
                        ). Initially, the CDsomesnuc rapidly distributed on the plasma membrane and in the cytoplasm, then accumulated around the nucleus, and finally distributed in the nucleoli. To further demonstrate the energy-independent diffusion of the CDsomes/CDs into the cells, Hela cells were first treated with sodium azide (NaN3) to block the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP), and then incubated with CDsomes/CDs (Havrdová et al., 2021). As shown in Fig. S10, the fluorescence intensities and distribution of the CDsomes or CDs in the cells pre-treated with NaN3 exhibit no significant difference from the untreated (control) groups, supporting energy-independent processes for the entry of CDsomes/CDs into the cells. Moreover, to elucidate the localization of the CDsomesnuc in the nucleoli, ribonuclease A (RNase) was selected to hydrolyze the RNA of HeLa cells, followed by CDsomesnuc-staining. As depicted in Fig. S11A, nucleoli could still be clearly visualized by CDsomesnuc, which was in marked contrast to that stained by SYTO RNASelect (RNA selective dye, Fig. S11B), ascribing to the reduction of RNA content in the nucleoli. Electrostatic interaction with the nucleolar proteins rich in basic amino acids appeared to be the driving force behind the nucleolar localization of CDsomesnuc due to their high negative charge (ca. −74 mV) (Aris and Blobel, 1991; Gotzmann et al., 1997). To the best of our knowledge, this is the first report of CDs with nucleolus-targeting capability but not mediated by rRNA binding (Yin et al., 2020; Hua et al., 2019; Jiang et al., 2020). Further research is required to explore their full potential in nucleolar-oriented applications. On the other hand, the CDscyto and CDsomesmem individually cannot achieve nucleolar localization, suggesting that CDsomesnuc may act as a delivery vesicle for nuclear entry of hydrophilic CDs, which eventually enable the encapsulated CDs to translocate into the nucleoli. To elucidate the nuclear entry process of hydrophilic CDs, a traditional liposome, consisting of l-α-phosphatidylserine, was employed to encapsulate CDscyto to demonstrate the nuclear entry process of CDs (Fig. S12). The DNA binding dye, DAPI (4′,6-diamidino-2-phenylindole), was used for labeling of nuclear membrane and boundaries of nucleoli. Green fluorescence from CDscyto in the nucleoli indicated that liposome-encapsulated CDscyto achieved nucleolar localization, which further supported our reasoning of CDsomesmem–assisted delivery of CDscyto to nucleoli in living cells.
